A charged particle of mass me and charge ¬±e in an attractive Coulomb potential can be modeled using the Hamiltonian

I2 and I4 denote the identity matrix of size 2×2 and 4×4 respectively. The Dirac equation has particle spin incorporated into the kinetic term. This will be clear once we expand the equation in spherical coordinates

Spin appears in the off diagonal angular momentum terms of the reduced matrix above. J2-L2-S2 term is the result of the spin-orbit coupling S¬∑L. J is the total angular momentum operator, L is the usual orbital angular momentum operator, and S is the spin angular momentum operator.

Since the Hamiltonian is a 4×4 matrix, the wavefunction solution is a four-component vector. The component functions that solve this system of differential equations are all individually separable. The wavefunction takes the form of

The first index in the column vector denotes the charge of the particle with – corresponding to a charge of -e, an electron, and + to a charge of +e, a positron (anti-electron). The second index denotes the spin state of the particle. +,- representing spin state +1/2 and -1/2, respectively.

Furthermore, there exists two class of solutions to the Dirac equation. One for when j=l+1/2 and one for j=l-1/2. Solving the Dirac equation yields the wavefunction

where LdN(x) is the generalized Laguerre polynomial, Ylm(Œ∏,œï) the usual spherical harmonics, Œ± is the fine structure constant (Note that Œ± is different than Œ±), a0 the Bohr radius, Kn,l,j a normalization constant, and Œª, Œ≥, a defined as

The index n,l,j,mj completely describe the quantum state of the system. n and l are the normal principal and orbital quantum numbers. j and mj are the quantum numbers associated with the total angular momentum operator J=L+S, and the projected total angular momentum operator Jz. j takes on values of either j=l+1/2 or j=l-1/2. The values of mj=ml+ms=ml¬±1/2 and mj‚àà{-j,-j+1,‚Ä¶,j-1,j}.

The energy associated with the eigenstate œàn,l,j,mj is

and the binding energy of the associated state is Œµn,j=En,j-mec2. In the Dirac model, some of the degeneracies in energy have been lifted. It is important to note that due to the mass-energy equivalence in relativity, spontaneous pair production is possible and the interpretation of |œà|2 as a probability density breaks down as particle number is no longer a conserved quantity. For the ground state œà1,0,1/2,¬±1/2, the energy eigenvalue E1,1/2 becomes imaginary when Z > 1/Œ±‚âà137 (This limit has been extended to ~173 by allowing for a finite size nucleus). For large Z~137, a field model of the Dirac equation is required as the single particle approach is no longer valid. In our case, Z=1 and we are well below the high energy limit of the Dirac wavefunction model.

Since the probability density is given by |œà|2= |œà-,+|2+|œà-,-|2+|œà+,+|2+|œà+,-|2, the positron components contribute to the total probability. At low energies, un,l,j‚â´vn,l,j and the positron contribution is minimal. As Z increases (high energy limit), the positron contribution becomes significant.

The energy eigenstates probability density in the Dirac model are also cylindrically symmetric. The only œï dependence of the wavefunction is in the spherical harmonics, which does not appear in the probability density. Therefore a planar cross-section, œÅ-z plane, is sufficient in describing the spatial distribution of the electron-positron cloud.

item.content:encoded:
This is not a complete course on concepts in quantum mechanics. We assume the audience had at least a semester in undergraduate quantum mechanics. The derivation of the wavefunction(s) along with many core concepts have been left out. There are many sources that develop quantum mechanic more fully than we will. We suggests Introduction to Quantum Mechanics by Griffiths or Modern Quantum Mechanics by Sakurai as starting resources on the subject. We will try to develop basic concepts to understand the visuals presented. The main goal is to visualize the single electron hydrogen atom in the framework of quantum mechanics as described by the Schr√∂dinger equation and Dirac equation.

We will start by considering the simplest case. A single electron in the presence of a central nuclear potential. A non-relativistic electron in a spherical potential, namely the Coulomb potential, can be modeled using the Schr√∂dinger equation

where the probability density of the electron is given by |œà|2=œà*œà. The Hamiltonian above assumes a stationary nucleus of charge Ze. Motion of the nucleus can be introduced by taking the reduced mass, Œº=mNme/(mN+me), where mN is the mass of the nucleus, instead of the electron mass, me. We can define the correction factor as M=1/(1+me/mN) and it is clear that M approaches unity for heavy nuclei. For a hydrogen atom, M‚âà0.99946. For our purposes, it is sufficient to consider a stationary nucleus
relative to the electron motion.

Since the Hamiltonian has spherical symmetry, we choose to work in spherical coordinates. The Schr√∂dinger equation expands to become

The solutions to this differential equation is separable and takes the form of

where Rn,l(r) describes the radial distribution and the spherical harmonics Ylml(Œ∏,œï) describes the angular distribution. These functions are defined as

where LŒ±N(x) is the generalized Laguerre polynomial and Plml(x) is the associated Legendre polynomial. a0 is the Bohr radius for an electron in the hydrogen atom. It is useful to note that the only œï dependence of the wavefunction œàn,l,ml(r,Œ∏,œï) is exp(imlœï). The consequence of this is the probability density given by |œàn,l,ml(r,Œ∏,œï)|2 is independent of œï and therefore has cylindrical symmetry. It is enough to view the planar cross-section described by the œÅ-z plane where œÅ is the radial vector projection onto the azimuthal plane.

The index n,l,ml describe the eigenstate(s) of the Hamiltonian associated with the eigenvalue E. n is
typically referred to as the principal quantum number and uniquely determines the energy level of the atom, i.e. the eigenvalue E is only dependent on n, E ‚Üí En. Solving for the energy in the Schr√∂dinger equation yields

The principal quantum number takes on any positive integer values, n‚àà‚Ñ§+. The orbital quantum number l describes the shape of the orbital. This is evident in the fact that both the radial and angular functions depend on l. In fact, there are l angular nodes and n-l-1 radial nodes. Of the l angular nodes, |ml| of the nodes lie in the x-y plane while the remaining l-|ml| nodes lie in the œÅ-z plane. Values of l are non-negative integer up to and including n-1, l‚àà{0,1,‚Ä¶,n-1}. ml is the magnetic quantum number. It determines the shift in energy levels of atomic orbitals in the presence of an external magnetic field. Values of ml are from -l to +l in integer steps, ml‚àà{-l,-l+1,‚Ä¶,l-1,l}.

The charge of the nucleus does not affect the overall shape of the orbitals. The dependence on the charge, Z, is only in the radial function and energy eigenvalue. This means that the charge only affects how tightly bounded the electron is. The charge, Z, sets the scale size of the orbitals and the binding energy of the state. This is what we would expect given the Coulomb potential.

Electrons are fermions with spin 1/2. The quantum numbers s and ms describe the spin state of the electron. The solution to the Schr√∂dinger equation with a static electric potential does not account for the spin nature of the electron. The energy eigenstates for an electron bound to a nucleus can be extended to include spin by taking

where œáms are eigenstates of the spin operator, S2, and the spin projection operator, Sz. For an electron,
ms=¬±1/2 which corresponds to alignment and anti-alignment with the z-axis, and are the eigenvalues of Sz (the eigenvalues are ¬±‚Ñè/2 when using S.I. units). The spin states do not affect the electron probability distribution of pure eigenstates in the Schr√∂dinger model in the absence of an external magnetic field. The inclusion of spin in our model is for the completeness of the quantum state.

The wavefunctions œàn,l,ml are energy eigenstates of the Hamiltonian for an electron in a Coulomb potential with energy eigenvalues given by En. Any normalized linear combinations of these eigenstates are valid solutions to the Hamiltonian and are valid states for the electron.

Earlier we stated that in our basis of choice, the energy eigenstates of the Hamiltonian has cylindrical symmetry. We can break this symmetry in the probability density and observe the angular nodes in the x-y plane by changing basis. We will define the new basis functions Œ®n,l,ml* in terms of œàn,l,ml basis functions as

where ml* acts exactly like ml of the old basis, ml*‚àà{-l,-l+1,‚Ä¶,l-1,l}. The new basis functions Œ®n,l,ml* are still energy eigenstates of the Hamiltonian.

Spectroscopic Notation

We will denote the eigenstates in spectroscopic notation. The standard notation for state is

where s is the total spin momentum, L is the total orbital angular momentum, j is the total angular momentum. Since we’re looking at a single electron, s=1/2, in state œàn,l,ml , we will use a slightly modified (and nonstandard) notation where we denote ml,ms instead of j.

The letter L is given by the mapping

with l‚â•4 continuing alphabetically, only skipping J, i.e. l=7 corresponds to K.

Later on, we will work in the total angular momentum basis and we will modify the standard notation by including mj to denote the state given by œàn,l,j,mj .
